  "definitions": [],
  "secText": [
    "  <b>Essential Question: </b>  <b>    <br />  </b>How does heat transfer?",
    "  <b>Enduring Understandings:</b>  <b>    <br />  </b>1. <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='11' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='1' data-subsection='0'>Conduction</a> is the heat transfer due to contact within or between objects. <br />2. <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='11' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='2' data-subsection='0'>Convection</a> is the heat transfer due to motion of molecules within fluids. An example of convection is warm air rising.<br />3. <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='11' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='3' data-subsection='0'>Electromagnetic radiation</a> is the transfer of energy by electric and magnetic fields. An example of electromagnetic radiation is the <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='11' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='3' data-subsection='1'>Sun's energy</a> heating <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='11' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='3' data-subsection='2'>Earth's atmosphere </a>.<br />4. <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='11' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='4' data-subsection='0'>Conduction, convection, and electromagnetic radiation</a> all deal with the idea of heat transfer, but vary in how heat is transferred.",
    "  <b>Vocabulary:</b>  <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='11' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='1' data-subsection='0'>conduction</a>, <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='11' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='2' data-subsection='0'>convection</a>, <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='11' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='3' data-subsection='0'>electromagnetic radiation</a>, <a class='pjumpToTopic' href='javascript:void(0)' data-chap='11' data-topic='5' data-subtopic='3' data-subsection='2'>global warming</a>"
  ],
